html.p:
Given two sets \[ \{ a, b ,c \}, \{1, 2 , 3\} \]
Each member of the first set can be paired off uniquely.j
\begin{align} a &\to 1 \\ b &\to 2 \\ c &\to 3 \end{align}

html.def:
Let `f: A \to B`,


  1) if `C \subset A`, we define

  \begin{align}
  f(C) &= \{ y \in B, \exists x \in C, y = f(x) \} \\
       &= \{ f(x) : x \in C \}.
  \end{align}

html.p:
Given the sets `A` and `B` illustrated above, let's see how
`f` maps some subsets from `A` to `B`.

\begin{align}
f(C) &= \{ y \in B, \exists x \in C, y = f(x) \} \\
     &= \{ f(x) : x \in C \}
\end{align}

f(\{1, 2\}) &= \{a\} 
f(\{1, 3\}) &= \{a, c\}
f^{-1}(\{ a \}) &= \{1, 2\}
f^{-1}(\{a,c,d \}) &= \{1,2,3,4\}
